explanation:
According to Article 36, Paragraph 4, Subparagraphs "a", "b", and "g" of the Law of Georgia on "Traffic Rules", at an uncontrolled intersection: 
a) The driver of a vehicle on a secondary road must yield to the approaching vehicle on the main road, regardless of its subsequent direction of travel; 
b) If the main road changes direction at the intersection, drivers on that road must follow the rules for passing equal-weighted roads. Drivers on the secondary road must also follow these rules; 
g) At the crossing of equal-weighted roads, the driver of a non-powered vehicle must yield to the approaching vehicle from the right. Drivers of rail vehicles must also follow this rule.

According to paragraph 2 of article 36 of the "Law on Road Traffic" of Georgia, an intersection where the order of movement is determined by traffic lights or signals from a traffic controller is considered a regulated intersection. If the yellow flashing signal is on, or if there is no traffic light or it is not functioning, or if there is no traffic controller, the intersection is considered unregulated, and the driver is obliged to follow the rules for passing through an unregulated intersection and the priority signs placed at the intersection. According to subparagraphs "g" and "d" of paragraph 4 of the same article, at an unregulated intersection: 
g) When crossing equal priority roads, the driver of a vehicle without rails must yield to a vehicle approaching from the right. Rail-bound vehicles must also follow this rule among each other. At such an intersection, rail-bound vehicles have priority over vehicles without rails, regardless of their direction of movement; 
d) When turning left or making a U-turn, the driver of a vehicle without rails must yield to vehicles moving directly or turning right from the opposite direction on an equal priority road. Rail-bound vehicles must also follow this rule among each other.

According to subparagraphs "g," "v," and "z" of paragraph 3 of article 30 of the "Traffic Code" of Georgia, road traffic is regulated by authorized persons of the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Georgia. Within the framework of powers granted by Georgian legislation, the regulation of road traffic may also be carried out by: 
g) rescuers and individuals participating in rescue operations, - to ensure the execution of rescue operations; 
v) railway employees - at railway crossings; 
z) organizers of ferry transportation - at the port.

According to the first paragraph of Article 37 of the Law of Georgia on Road Traffic, a vehicle that stops or stands in an uninhabited area must be located outside the roadway, within feasible limits. According to subparagraphs “b” of the first paragraph and “b” of the second paragraph of Article 52 of the same law: 
1. Emergency light signaling is used to warn other participants in road traffic about an imminent danger. The emergency lights must be turned on at the location of forced stopping where stopping is prohibited;
2. After activating the emergency lights, and also if such signaling is absent or malfunctioning, the driver must immediately display the "emergency stop sign," and under conditions of insufficient visibility - a flashing red light at locations where stopping is prohibited and where, considering visibility conditions, other drivers will not be able to notice the vehicle in time.

According to paragraph "a.b" of subparagraph 6 of Article 37 of the law "On Road Traffic" of Georgia, it is prohibited to stop vehicles on the roadway, on the tramways and railway tracks, or near them if it can hinder the movement of trams or trains. According to subparagraphs "b.e" and "b.v" of the same paragraph, it is prohibited to stop vehicles in any place where it can create a danger, including:  
b.e) in a place where it obscures traffic light indications or road signs for other road users;  
b.v) on an additional traffic lane designated for slow-moving vehicles as indicated by the relevant road sign.

According to paragraph 2 subparagraphs "a", "b", and "d" of Article 39 of the Law of Georgia on "Road Traffic", the following actions are prohibited at a railway crossing:  
a) Overtaking a vehicle that is stationary in front of the crossing by entering the opposite lane;  
b) Unauthorized opening of a barrier or half-barrier;  
d) Movement of slow-moving vehicles, not exceeding a speed of 8 km/h, and tractor trailers without the permission of the railway track distance supervisor.
